    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3088281527" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3088281527" />
    <a title="Prerna" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/79765515-prerna"><img alt="Prerna" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1624507324p2/79765515.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3088281527?book_show_action=true">May 01, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Prerna" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Prerna" href="/user/show/79765515-prerna">Prerna</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/79765515-prerna?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/79765515-prerna?shelf=feminism">feminism</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3088281527" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1660410214106957490">I picked up this book because I have participated in far too many discussions with friends and acquaintances trying to convince them of the actual meaning of the feminist movement while failing miserably. Patriarchy is ingrained into the Indian social order, I was hoping this book would give me some insight as to how to approach people who have formed inaccurate, preconceived notions regarding feminism. Oh what a huge disappointment!<br/><br/>The first thing to note about this book is that the title is ex</span>
  <span id="freeText1660410214106957490" style="display:none">I picked up this book because I have participated in far too many discussions with friends and acquaintances trying to convince them of the actual meaning of the feminist movement while failing miserably. Patriarchy is ingrained into the Indian social order, I was hoping this book would give me some insight as to how to approach people who have formed inaccurate, preconceived notions regarding feminism. Oh what a huge disappointment!<br /><br />The first thing to note about this book is that the title is extremely misleading. It is not in any way an introductory book to the feminist movement.<br /><br />The book is in many ways ironic. hooks stresses on the importance of intersectional feminism while refusing to accept the diversity of opinions within feminist circles and that the meaning of 'empowerment' can be purely subjective in many cases. <br /><br />hooks repeatedly talks about how the academization of feminism has alienated the general mass from its causes while the frequency of her own usage of academic terms of feminist theory increases with each chapter.<br /><br />In many chapters the book serves as an advertising platform for the author's previous works and she tries to demonstrate how her own stands opposing those of radical and visionary feminism are more progressive and necessary to the current feminist movement while not making any convincing arguments.<br /><br />The most harmful thing about this book is the large number of claims the author makes without presenting any evidence. There are no citations to statistical data, studies, peer-reviewed papers or even articles. Consider for example:<br /><br /> "Visionary lesbians were far more willing to take on the issue of interrogating white supremacy than their straight comrades. And they were more likely to desire to strengthen bonds with all men. The vast majority of straight women, whether they were actively feminist or not, were more concerned about their relationships with men."<br /><br />I don't know how qualified I am to write this review, since I picked up this book in December and gave up halfway through. But this book is definitely not for everybody. It is only for a certain section of women of western societies. This book does not explain the nuances and multi-dimensionality of feminism. No, it tells you exactly what you ought to do to be considered a feminist.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1660410214106957490" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

