        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3800312610" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8291707618742396831">i&apos;m not sure how to express my distaste for this book. clearly i am not an expert on feminism considering i am reading this for a 101 course in women&apos;s and gender studies and ik bell hooks is a respected writer on the topic.<br/><br/>she makes a few good points, usually about how race impacts feminism and about how men also can be affected negatively by a patriarchal society.<br/><br/>but this book didn&apos;t do what it said it would - intro to feminism - and was full of literally nothing but her opinions of &apos;who count</span>
  <span id="freeText8291707618742396831" style="display:none">i'm not sure how to express my distaste for this book. clearly i am not an expert on feminism considering i am reading this for a 101 course in women's and gender studies and ik bell hooks is a respected writer on the topic.<br /><br />she makes a few good points, usually about how race impacts feminism and about how men also can be affected negatively by a patriarchal society.<br /><br />but this book didn't do what it said it would - intro to feminism - and was full of literally nothing but her opinions of 'who counted' or however you want to frame it. hardly 'everybody' like the title professes - she shames and puts down a heck ton of people just casually for a variety of reasons and acts as if what she says is fact. there was no acknowledgement of trans people and everything she said about sex and sexuality was disgusting, framing sexuality as a 'choice', giving opinions on what made a woman 'sexually liberated' (spoiler: sex workers? apparently they're shameful, don't count, fundamentally antifeminist), and how sexual pleasure is incredibly important, necessary to a fulfilling life, and what 'connects us all as humans' or something equally ://<br /><br />idk. there's a lot that rubbed me the wrong way.</span>
